description:
Swipe left, feel empty, and wonder why? Esther Perel reveals the hidden truths behind the dating crisis, loneliness, and the shocking decline in sex and intimacy.

Esther Perel is a world-renowned psychotherapist and relationship expert, widely recognised as one of todays most insightful and original voices on modern relationships. She is the bestselling author of books such as, The State of Affairs. 


She explains: 
緒 Why MEN Over 30 Arent Having Sex Anymore.
緒 The SEX GAME that could Save Your Relationship.
緒 How CHILDHOOD TRAUMA is Secretly Sabotaging Your Marriage.
緒 Why Investing in AUTHENTIC CONNECTION is the key to a Fulfilling Life.
緒 The ONE RED FLAG that Predicts Divorce.

comments.text:
As someone who has been since his 20s pro-active, flirty, chatty, extrovert, polivalent when it comes to tastes and hobbies and had frequented several social circles (like expats or latin dances) I'm finding terribly difficult to have satisfactory approaches to women whether it's online or real live.

The response cost has spiked.
I believed we're so exposed to ideas and labels that automatically have some named box to put into whatever stimulus we're confronting not doing the work of experimenting and making sense for it in hour lives four ourselves.

In apps (Tinder, Bumble, etc) the likes I received have decreased dramatically (from 10-20 4 years ago to barely 2) even opening the account after a cold down period and having being living in different citties. I checked with female friends to see if there was something wrong with my profile but they praised it.

The apps toy with you, not showing the few profiles that allegedly liked you recently until you have used up a couple of days worth of swipe limit.

Despite the modern narrative women still don't take the iniciative in the interaction and when they do they do in the same bland low effort ways they collectively spend there bio rejecting and complaining. I can't get over the fact how someone decide to spend those few words to speak shit and complains instead of making points of interest for bonding. Most of the time matches don't even answer or start the conversation (in case of Bumble). Most women who still inherited the role of filtering don't use the apps in a mindfull way (accumulating likes and getting overwhelmed by them for example).

Flirting in real life has gotten rarified too. Women still don't take the iniciative or they do it based on physycal appearence and virtue signalling more than any other time I can recall. I move in the progressist spectrum and it has become asfixiatingly disonant how tolerance and openness is praised while connections are atomized by identity labelling. Seems that the only thing everybody wants now is something that check all the boxes of their fantasy.

Still this wouldn't stop me to look for approaching people I like in a flirtacious way but thinks have become so unclear, people are getting so evasive and taking the risk of approaching and being wrong has become so condemnable that I just don't wanna add fuel to the fire (to the social discussion) even I've got used to personal rejection through repetitions throughout my life.

As I say. The response cost has risen for all but particularly those who care about it.
I understand where we come from and it wasn't a nice place for women (or non normative people, even I haven't considered mysef normative ever either).
Meanwhile, shitty people that don't give a fuck about social discussion or peoples feelings continue doing their bidding and women continue giving them protagonism while confessing them as a guilty plessure "oopsie" in their instagram stories. Sure, being handsome isn't exclusive of being good or intelligent but it seems the first is being prioritised despite evidence about the second.

I'm sad because after years of personal growth, career shift towards more ethical goals and compromise with my field while still being and open minded, healthy, versatile, caring person I've never felt so outcasted and context innappropriate than nowadays.
I feel the best thing I can do to attract women is to become a gymbro so there's less questions asked and being socially mindful and skillful in a nearly psychopathic way cuz there's no room left for genuinity (unless you signal it with some variation of flag).

PS: Let me be clear I'm but no means neglecting men's historic general role as a collective or dating apps companies tactics. I'm just pointing out some perceived behaviour that frustrates me as, while I can understand in the context of retaliation (unthoughtful, uncontrolled, weaponized) I cannot see it in the context of building a better place for all of us.

comments.text:
I think settling is one of the most mature understandings of this life, meaning this... if you are always striving to know 100% of yourself (physically, mentally, emotionally, and spiritually), how could you possibly be 100% of what someone else would want? Settling is humility, and confidence, because it shows you give yourself grace, and the more grace you have for yourself, the more grace you have for others. And the law of attraction will apply.

We are in the AI era, and while others might see it as scary (and yes, it has its dark sides), we can also see it as it taking over all of mundane physical tasks so we have more time for one another. People aren't supposed to be using AI to date. It's the most efficient when it makes your work easier so that you can free up time for the people you want to meet, grow with, and love...

We will transcend and evolve to this, eventually. We're all in a learning curve, right now, that's all.

Excellent episode as always, Steven and team  Thank you. And Ester, phenomenal  I learned so much from you and I appreciate your work  We might agree to disagree... but I believe transparency is the best policy. Yes, to be tactful (not every situation calls for "brutal" honesty, but soft honesty), but honesty should still be shared. We are moving into an era where that is all we're going to have of each other to depend on  and transparency is a beautiful thing
